     1	# Slice 003J: Background Job Scheduling Foundation
     2	
     3	## Status
     4	Not Started
     5	
     6	## Parent Epic
     7	Epic 003: Audit, Documents, Config, and Dashboard Foundation
     8	Epic file: `docs/epics/003-audit-documents-config-foundation.md`
     9	
    10	## Goal
    11	Add a minimal backend background-job scheduling foundation that later slices can use for reminders,
    12	async reports, and notification generation without sending real communications or running external
    13	workers in this slice.
    14	
    15	## User Value
    16	Moves the platform one verifiable step closer to a working end-to-end lending system without broad module-sized changes.
    17	
    18	## Depends On
    19	- 003IA
    20	
    21	## Source References
    22	- docs/source/implementation-roadmap.md sections 10, 20-22
    23	- docs/source/api-contracts.md sections 26, 39, 41, 42-43
    24	- docs/source/data-model.md document/config/audit tables
    25	- docs/source/component-spec.md
    26	- docs/source/design-system.md
    27	
    28	## Prototype Reference
    29	- sfpcl-lms/src/pages/Dashboard.tsx
    30	- sfpcl-lms/src/pages/tasks/TaskInbox.tsx
    31	- sfpcl-lms/src/components/loan/AuditTimeline.tsx
    32	- sfpcl-lms/src/components/loan/DocumentPackModal.tsx
    33	
    34	## Screens Involved
    35	None directly.
    36	
    37	## Frontend Scope
    38	None for this slice, except updating frontend documentation or fixtures if required by tests.
    39	
    40	## Backend/API Scope
    41	Implement only a local scheduler/job metadata shell:
    42	- A model for scheduled jobs with source-neutral fields: job id, job type/code, status, due/run time,
    43	  related entity type/id when applicable, attempts, last error summary, created/updated timestamps.
    44	- A small service boundary to enqueue a job idempotently and mark it running/succeeded/failed for
    45	  future modules.
    46	- No Celery/Redis/cloud scheduler dependency unless already pinned and importable.
    47	- No real email/SMS/courier delivery, no reminder generation business rules, no report generation,
    48	  and no automatic notification creation beyond what 003IA already does for communication sends.
    49	
    50	## Database/Model Impact
    51	Non-destructive model/migration changes for this capability, if needed.
    52	
    53	## API Contracts
    54	If an endpoint is added, record it in `docs/working/API_CONTRACTS.md` with standard envelopes,
    55	strict query validation, and top-level pagination. Keep it clearly separate from
    56	`/api/v1/dashboard/`, `/api/v1/notifications/`, and `/api/v1/communications/`.
    57	
    58	## Permissions
    59	Use the narrowest existing administrative/ops permission. If source docs do not name a scheduler
    60	permission, record the assumption in `ASSUMPTIONS.md`; do not reuse communication-send or dashboard
    61	permissions for scheduler administration.
    62	
    63	## Audit Requirements
    64	Audit metadata-only scheduler mutations if exposed through an API. Do not audit raw rendered
    65	message bodies, provider payloads, or report contents.
    66	
    67	## Validation Rules
    68	Validate job type/status values, related entity UUIDs, idempotency keys if supported, and legal
    69	state transitions. Do not invent reminder timing, report cadence, or notification business rules.
    70	
    71	## Test Cases
    72	- Service tests for enqueue idempotency and legal/illegal status transitions.
    73	- API tests, if an endpoint is added, for `401`, `403`, strict query validation, pagination, and no
    74	  provider side effects.
    75	- Regression test that dashboard tasks and notification inbox rows are not generated by the
    76	  scheduler shell in this slice.
    77	
    78	## Visual Acceptance Criteria
    79	None.
    80	
    81	## Evidence Required
    82	Test output, API response examples, and screenshots when frontend is touched.
    83	
    84	## Risk Level
    85	Medium
    86	
